In modern industries and smart systems, machines and equipment generate huge amounts of operational data every day. Unexpected equipment failure can cause major financial loss, production downtime, maintenance cost increases, and safety risks. Traditional maintenance methods such as reactive maintenance (repair after failure) and scheduled maintenance (fixed servicing intervals) are often inefficient because they cannot accurately determine the real condition of equipment.

Many organizations still struggle to detect early warning signs of machine failure from sensor and operational data. As systems become more complex, manual monitoring becomes difficult, time-consuming, and unreliable. Small anomalies or hidden patterns that indicate future failure are often missed by human operators.

Machine learning techniques can help solve this problem by analyzing historical machine data and predicting possible failures before they happen. However, building an accurate predictive maintenance system is challenging because industrial datasets are often large, noisy, imbalanced, and contain many irrelevant features. Different machine learning algorithms perform differently depending on the quality and structure of the dataset.

Another challenge is that most prediction systems only provide failure outputs without explaining the reason behind the prediction. This lack of interpretability reduces user trust and makes it difficult for engineers and operators to take proper maintenance actions.

To address these problems, this project proposes a Predictive Maintenance System using Machine Learning and AI Assistance. The system uses algorithms such as Random Forest and XGBoost to predict machine failure and calculate failure probability based on operational and sensor data. In addition, an LLM-based AI Assistant is integrated to explain prediction risks, provide maintenance suggestions, and answer user queries in natural language.

The proposed system aims to improve maintenance efficiency, reduce downtime, increase equipment reliability, and support intelligent decision-making in industrial environments.